ST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from either of two places in Dumfriess called Kirkpatrick or any of various other places in Scotland, all so named from the dedication of their church to Saint Patrick. The Scottish word <i>kirk</i> sometimes replaced Gaelic <i>cill</i> ‘church’ in placenames; compare   Kilpatrick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilpatrick","meanings":["Irish (Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phádraig</b> ‘son of the servant of (Saint) Patrick’ (Irish <i>Pádraig</i>). See also   Fitzpatrick  .","Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called in Gaelic as <i>cill Padraig</i> ‘church of (Saint) Patrick’. See also   Kirkpatrick  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Kirkpatrick was born about 1556, in Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Kirkpatrick, was 25 and his mother, Elizabeth Hamilton, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Kirkpatrick."},"et":{"Abt 1556–":"umbes 1556–Surnud","1556–Male":"1556–Surnud","1560–Female":"1560–Surnud","1580–1645":"1580–1645","1533–Male":"1533–Surnud","1533–Female":"1533–Surnud","1645":"1645","1556":"1556","1533":"1533","Abt 1556":"umbes 1556","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","Closeburn, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Closeburn, Dumfries, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi"